WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.040
Welcome back to the Data Science Hangout. I'm Rachel, I lead Customer Marketing at Posit,

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:20.760
and I'm so excited to have you joining us today. If it's your first time joining us,

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:25.200
the Hangout is our open space to hear what's going on in the world of data across different

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:31.280
industries, chat about data science leadership, and connect with others facing similar things as

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:38.720
you. And we get together here every Thursday at the same time, same place. If it is your first

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:44.439
Hangout, let us know in the chat because we would love to welcome you in for anybody joining the

00:00:44.439 --> 00:00:50.240
first time. We are all dedicated to keeping this a friendly and welcoming space for everyone,

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:56.919
so we love to hear from you no matter your years of experience, titles, industry, or languages that

00:00:56.919 --> 00:01:03.480
you work in. It's also totally okay if you just want to listen in here too. Maybe you're on your

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:09.279
lunch break or you're out walking your dog, but also awesome to be a part of the party that will

00:01:09.279 --> 00:01:14.360
happen in the Zoom chat. So you may meet a few people there in the Zoom chat, see a lot of great

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:21.360
resources shared as well. But there's three ways that you can jump in and ask questions or provide

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:27.559
your own perspective on topics. So you can raise your hand on Zoom and I'll call on you to jump in.

00:01:27.559 --> 00:01:33.839
You can put questions in the Zoom chat and just put a little star next to it if it's something you

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:40.440
want me to read out loud. And then third, we have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:48.279
We do also, I sometimes forget to say this, but we do also have a LinkedIn group for the Hangout,

00:01:48.279 --> 00:01:56.120
if anybody wants to join there. It's not great for discussions, but it's awesome for being able

00:01:56.120 --> 00:02:02.879
to connect with everybody and more easily find each other. Quick note though, if you are watching

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:08.160
this as a recording on YouTube in the future and you want to join us live, the link to add it to

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:14.440
your calendar is going to be in the details below. And as always, there's no rule that you have to

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:21.039
stay on the whole time or talk, come and go as it fits your own schedule. But with that, I am so

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:28.080
excited to be joined by my co-host today, Brad Zelke, Senior Director of Data Sciences at Target.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:34.600
And Brad, I'd love to have you kick us off here by introducing yourself and sharing a little bit

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:38.440
about your role and also something you like to do outside of work.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:48.279
Perfect. Thanks, Rachel, for having me. Nice to virtually meet everybody. Really quick, so I'm a Senior Director of Data Science at Target.

00:02:48.279 --> 00:02:58.479
I work in the operations space, so my team supports various decision modeling capabilities across everything from vendors

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:08.919
and our supply chain and transportation providers all the way through to what happens in our stores and also how we operate in our properties world.

00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:16.320
So when we talk about properties, we talk about construction, we talk about energy optimization, work like that.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:21.520
And so it's really fun space across Target because we actually touch everything that physically happens.

00:03:21.559 --> 00:03:27.000
So I have a fairly large global team that really makes it all happen.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.440
A little bit more about me, I've been with Target 20 years, so I have one job before Target and then I've been here ever since.

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:39.639
And I'll get into a little bit of this as we talk more, but I think the variety of work in data science and retail is just fascinating.

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:46.119
So across my 20 years, I've had opportunities to work in cybersecurity, work in supply chain, obviously stores.

00:03:46.119 --> 00:03:54.800
I've been able to work with HR analytics and other things, and it's just a really neat place where you can kind of cross domains in the industry as well.

00:03:54.800 --> 00:04:02.279
And then what I enjoy outside of work, so I have four kids. Four kids keeps me busy, but I love coaching sports and anything athletic and outdoor.

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:07.440
So I spend my time running. I'll run my sixth marathon this fall.

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:13.479
My sons are swimmers and hockey players, so my winters are packed either in a pool or on the ice.

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:15.320
And so that's what I enjoy doing outside of work.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:22.679
I love it. That's awesome. I was going to ask what sport you coach. Is it hockey?

00:04:22.679 --> 00:04:24.679
Hockey, yeah.

00:04:24.679 --> 00:04:33.399
Well, thank you so much for joining us here today, and I get to start us off with some questions as we wait for them all to come in from everybody here.

00:04:33.399 --> 00:04:39.160
But I was curious, Brad, being at Target for over 20 years,

00:04:39.399 --> 00:04:45.160
could you share a bit about the evolution that you've seen of data science in the retail space?

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:51.320
Yeah, absolutely. So Target probably, I've been around a long time.

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:55.640
So I started at Target doing statistical modeling in distribution centers.

00:04:56.279 --> 00:05:00.760
And what's fascinating is when I started, we only had 16 VCs in the country.

00:05:01.559 --> 00:05:02.920
Right now, we have over 60.

00:05:03.559 --> 00:05:07.320
And so you think about those localized models and solutions we were building.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:11.799
I've been part of seeing that grow and rapidly expand, too.

00:05:11.799 --> 00:05:15.799
At one point, we centralized that for the company, then we've extended it.

00:05:15.799 --> 00:05:22.440
And then over the last 10 years, this is really my third stint in and outside of data sciences at Target.

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:27.480
So at one point, BI and data analytics were all part of data sciences.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:33.480
And as we brought that together, we decided to build data products for Target.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:36.920
We started to formalize measurements and metrics across the organization.

00:05:37.799 --> 00:05:40.040
And then data sciences really grew rapidly.

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:42.359
And so we talked a lot more about decision models.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.119
So anything from recommendation systems to search to optimization and algorithm

00:05:48.119 --> 00:05:50.519
development that we do in operations today.

00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:55.320
And so I've seen this huge transformation into being very supportive and augmented

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:58.760
to the organization, to becoming more and more data science-led and forward,

00:05:59.399 --> 00:06:03.239
especially in these spaces where I think traditionally it would have been just

00:06:03.239 --> 00:06:11.959
statistical models or more of our objective decisioning and now becoming a lot more

00:06:12.519 --> 00:06:16.119
augmented in terms of leading the organization and new capabilities as well.

00:06:16.119 --> 00:06:20.600
So it's been a really fun journey that we continue to build on.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:23.559
Gen AI, obviously, is all the buzz right now.

00:06:23.559 --> 00:06:24.920
And we're dabbling in that.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:27.320
And it's just fun to see what else is possible.

00:06:27.559 --> 00:06:28.059
Absolutely.

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:32.600
And a quick follow-up question from your intro, which marathon are you running next?

00:06:33.480 --> 00:06:36.440
I'm running Twin Cities Marathon for the fifth time.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:42.359
And then I'm looking at doing Grandma's now that our winter has been so warm.

00:06:42.359 --> 00:06:45.720
We've been able to get outside and get some more miles in earlier in the season.

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:47.160
So I might run two this year.

00:06:48.040 --> 00:06:48.540
Nice.

00:06:50.679 --> 00:06:55.640
So just so everybody knows here, when we say data science and operations,

00:06:55.880 --> 00:07:00.440
could you share just an example of maybe a use case that you're working on now or

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:02.040
what that really means?

00:07:03.399 --> 00:07:03.899
Yeah.

00:07:03.899 --> 00:07:07.799
So as I alluded to, our teams work across all different parts of our operations,

00:07:07.799 --> 00:07:10.440
from supply chain to stores to properties.

00:07:13.079 --> 00:07:17.239
We work heavily in the optimization, OR, operations research space.

00:07:17.239 --> 00:07:23.160
So we build simulations or digital twins of what we're doing across our different businesses.

00:07:23.399 --> 00:07:28.920
We do a lot of forecasting work where we're helping outline what networks should expect

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:32.200
or how things will be moving or how to staff a store.

00:07:33.079 --> 00:07:36.200
And so our team works across all of these different operational teams

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:38.040
or trying to execute work in the field.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:41.959
And so right now, I think one of the things I'm most excited about in our space

00:07:41.959 --> 00:07:46.519
is how we're using the horizontal capabilities of simulation optimization

00:07:46.519 --> 00:07:50.839
to look at the inputs and outputs as we derive a network.

00:07:51.239 --> 00:07:56.760
As we derive a network of capabilities from what we buy and how we move it

00:07:56.760 --> 00:08:00.600
all the way to how that will end up in a target building.

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:04.279
And so we can start to look at what we're doing internationally,

00:08:04.279 --> 00:08:07.959
how that lands domestically in our ports or our decons,

00:08:07.959 --> 00:08:11.160
and how that ends up moving into our stores ultimately.

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:14.839
And so we have models and algorithms that are starting to outline and connect

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:17.640
different decision variables that happen upstream

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:20.119
into those decisions that we're making downstream as well.

00:08:21.559 --> 00:08:25.799
So when you go into a target,

00:08:25.799 --> 00:08:28.600
are you thinking about all those things as you're shopping?

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:32.359
Yes, absolutely.

00:08:33.239 --> 00:08:37.320
Often I'm either annoyed where we don't have something that I want

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:40.760
because that means something else happened wrong upstream

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:45.080
or I'm overzealous about something that looks great

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:47.719
because all the work that ended up making that reality.

00:08:48.599 --> 00:08:52.039
Something I meant to add in the beginning,

00:08:52.039 --> 00:08:53.640
I wanted to just remind everybody,

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:56.679
if anyone's hiring for roles,

00:08:56.679 --> 00:08:58.840
feel free to share that in the chat as well.

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:02.119
I know there's some people who are looking that are joining as well.

00:09:02.119 --> 00:09:06.520
So it's not spammy at all to share those roles in the chat too.

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:10.039
But I guess, Brad, I'll ask you as well.

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:13.320
Are you currently hiring for any roles at Target?

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:15.559
Yeah, we're always hiring.

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:20.359
So I'll make a plug where we're building out some new search teams.

00:09:21.159 --> 00:09:23.880
We're looking at work and our recommendation systems

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:25.640
and personalization capabilities.

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:28.359
And then even across MySpace

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:30.760
and kind of the operations side of the team,

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:33.799
where we're always looking for talent to augment

00:09:33.799 --> 00:09:36.520
and build out some of our teams here locally in Minneapolis

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:38.679
and then also in our Sunnyvale office.

00:09:39.719 --> 00:09:41.320
And some people maybe don't know this,

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:43.640
but Target does offer remote and hybrid work too

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:47.000
where we have teams that travel in and out across the country.

00:09:50.280 --> 00:09:52.919
So feel free to reach out to me afterwards if you're interested.

00:09:54.359 --> 00:09:58.119
Awesome. Is LinkedIn the best place to connect with you?

00:09:58.119 --> 00:09:59.640
Yeah, that's a great way to reach out.

00:09:59.640 --> 00:10:00.679
Okay, perfect.

00:10:01.559 --> 00:10:05.640
Curtis, I see you have a question here in the chat

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:08.919
or maybe you're starting a conversation here in the chat.

00:10:08.919 --> 00:10:10.840
Do you want to jump in and ask that?

00:10:11.159 --> 00:10:14.599
Anytime someone mentions Target and data science,

00:10:14.599 --> 00:10:16.840
the anecdotal story about how,

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:19.400
I think it was the marketing data science team had...

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:19.900
Of course.

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:21.799
I just wanted...

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:24.440
Basically, anytime anyone from Target shows up,

00:10:24.440 --> 00:10:26.440
I always ask them to confirm the story.

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:30.280
So maybe if you wouldn't mind kind of recapping it and sharing.

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:32.599
There's a few people who signed in their classes.

00:10:32.599 --> 00:10:36.919
Oh my gosh, it's like the atypical academic case study, right?

00:10:36.919 --> 00:10:38.919
Of like machine learning and machine learning

00:10:39.159 --> 00:10:41.960
of like machine learning and data science gone wrong.

00:10:42.599 --> 00:10:44.760
So those of you guys who maybe haven't seen the article,

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:48.919
obviously, or maybe you have and you just want to refresh here.

00:10:48.919 --> 00:10:55.640
But Target started sending recommendations ads to a family.

00:10:56.840 --> 00:11:00.919
And the father found out through some of those ads and details

00:11:00.919 --> 00:11:02.039
that his daughter was pregnant,

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.159
which then turned out that Target knew more about the situation

00:11:07.159 --> 00:11:09.559
and what was being purchased based on that behavior

00:11:09.559 --> 00:11:13.320
that provided us details and insights of how to use that

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:15.159
and offer other incentives,

00:11:15.799 --> 00:11:21.479
which could be pretty intrusive.

00:11:22.359 --> 00:11:23.960
But I think it was also very interesting

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:25.880
and highlighted the power of data.

00:11:25.880 --> 00:11:29.080
Now, how Target handled that and all of that,

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:31.719
we, I think, had to disclose some more information,

00:11:31.719 --> 00:11:34.520
I think led to other processes and good governance

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:35.239
that we're working through.

00:11:35.239 --> 00:11:38.840
But it's a great case study, a good example of the power of it,

00:11:38.840 --> 00:11:42.200
but also how to be a good steward of data science as well.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:46.919
That's the one you're alluding to, right, Curtis?

00:11:48.919 --> 00:11:49.719
Exactly, yeah.

00:11:50.679 --> 00:11:54.359
That's a very true story that I remember very dearly.

00:11:56.200 --> 00:11:59.000
It must be hard when something is used as a case study

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:00.039
in a lot of classes,

00:12:00.039 --> 00:12:04.599
but then becomes something that is always asked about too.

00:12:05.239 --> 00:12:05.559
Yes.

00:12:07.559 --> 00:12:09.719
But there's so much more to data science than that, right?

00:12:09.719 --> 00:12:12.119
I think that was obviously something that made the news,

00:12:12.119 --> 00:12:14.520
but tons of good things with it as well.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:18.760
I see, Rick, you just put a question in the chat.

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:19.640
You want to jump in here?

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:24.520
Oh, hi, Brett.

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:25.239
Thank you very much.

00:12:26.359 --> 00:12:27.159
Rick Hubbard here.

00:12:27.799 --> 00:12:32.599
I'm a retired practitioner and a university professor,

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:35.479
but I'm very intrigued by your remarks.

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:39.159
The question I have is your DS function

00:12:39.159 --> 00:12:42.440
sounds to be quite sophisticated, quite capable.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:45.559
Sounds like you have a breadth and a depth of competencies.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:50.280
I'm wondering to what degree do your business customers,

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:53.239
the other lines of business that you interact with,

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:57.080
to what degree do they understand DS

00:12:57.080 --> 00:12:59.640
and the work products your team produces,

00:13:00.679 --> 00:13:02.679
methods and practices you undertake?

00:13:03.400 --> 00:13:05.080
And in addition to that,

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:10.359
what accounts for the business side's degree of acumen

00:13:10.359 --> 00:13:12.440
in understanding who you guys are

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:14.119
and what you do and how you do it?

00:13:15.559 --> 00:13:18.280
Yeah, I'll start with the first question.

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:23.159
Our customers don't always understand what we're doing.

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:26.359
But I think what I emphasize with my team

00:13:26.359 --> 00:13:29.080
and some of my teams on this call

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:31.880
is we have a deep empathy for our customers,

00:13:31.880 --> 00:13:34.119
our partners, and the decisions they're making.

00:13:34.119 --> 00:13:35.640
And that's always our starting point.

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:38.760
I think that gives us a way to interact,

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:40.919
teach, educate, and bring them into

00:13:40.919 --> 00:13:43.400
and along with the solutions we might share with them.

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:45.640
I'll give you an example though.

00:13:45.640 --> 00:13:48.039
So I just took my whole leadership team

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:52.039
out to our office in California.

00:13:52.039 --> 00:13:54.359
And then we all went and did an immersion experience

00:13:54.359 --> 00:13:56.840
where we went and actually walked physical buildings.

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:59.559
We met with team members on the DC floors.

00:13:59.559 --> 00:14:02.679
We met with store service team members.

00:14:02.679 --> 00:14:04.760
And really we're highlighting and showing

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:05.960
where our work intersected

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:07.559
with what they see and do every day.

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:13.719
And that hands-on connection allowed us to get feedback

00:14:13.719 --> 00:14:15.479
in terms of what they see from our work.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:19.400
Also allowed us to build, I think, a deeper understanding

00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:21.719
of why we see disconnects often from our work.

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:25.000
And then just enabled us to even further educate

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.599
people in the field who maybe are like,

00:14:26.599 --> 00:14:27.719
why is this happening?

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:31.000
Some of the nuances of what we're doing in our models

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:32.679
that end up leading to that.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:34.520
And so we end up augmenting our stores

00:14:34.520 --> 00:14:36.919
with different decisioning models

00:14:36.919 --> 00:14:40.679
that change the tasks or the work that they have.

00:14:40.679 --> 00:14:44.440
And when that changes, we can tend to see questions

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:45.960
of like, what is driving this?

00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:47.640
This doesn't seem normal.

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:49.719
And so then we can kind of loop back with them

00:14:49.719 --> 00:14:52.840
and have more of a high touch education

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:54.200
or connection with them as well,

00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:56.280
which I think goes a super long way.

00:14:56.280 --> 00:14:59.080
And so we spend, I think, as a leadership team,

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:01.719
the majority of our job actually engaging,

00:15:01.719 --> 00:15:04.760
educating, and partnering with them to teach,

00:15:04.760 --> 00:15:07.880
train, and then drive kind of the focus on this work

00:15:07.880 --> 00:15:08.919
versus delivering it.

00:15:08.919 --> 00:15:11.080
And then we have really, really talented teams

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:13.960
who end up building it, interacting with them

00:15:13.960 --> 00:15:15.640
as we deploy it and trying to capture

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:16.919
as much feedback as we can.

00:15:16.919 --> 00:15:19.080
So we have a lot of success criteria

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:20.599
in the operations space specifically,

00:15:20.599 --> 00:15:22.760
where we not only just deploy

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:24.280
and then test and learn virtually,

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:26.039
but we actually go and audit

00:15:26.039 --> 00:15:28.280
and look at our physical impacts as well,

00:15:28.280 --> 00:15:29.799
which I think is really, really unique.

00:15:31.559 --> 00:15:34.760
Brad, one of the reasons I'm asking is years ago,

00:15:35.559 --> 00:15:36.919
to show you how old I am,

00:15:36.919 --> 00:15:38.440
but you can tell from my white hair,

00:15:39.159 --> 00:15:41.080
I helped implement what was called

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:43.080
a information center.

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:45.719
It was considered to be revolutionary.

00:15:45.719 --> 00:15:48.200
My gosh, how old is that?

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:50.599
But one of the things we did that I,

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:53.559
so we implemented this information center

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:57.400
and it was in largely a financial institution,

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:00.760
broadly just geographically distributed

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:02.119
financial institution,

00:16:02.119 --> 00:16:04.520
and early results were desultory.

00:16:05.239 --> 00:16:07.479
So I thought over and said, what's going on here?

00:16:07.479 --> 00:16:10.200
And I realized, I went out and talked

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:12.840
to some of our prospective business customers,

00:16:14.119 --> 00:16:15.719
partners that we would support

00:16:15.719 --> 00:16:18.119
in the operation side.

00:16:19.239 --> 00:16:21.960
They didn't know how to engage with us.

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:23.400
They knew we existed.

00:16:23.400 --> 00:16:26.760
They knew we could answer certain problems

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:29.320
and gather data and do forecasts

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:30.119
and all that jazz,

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:32.919
but they didn't actually know how to engage with us.

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:33.960
So I did a little,

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:35.479
we put together a little course.

00:16:35.479 --> 00:16:37.159
I had my folks put together a little course

00:16:37.159 --> 00:16:40.760
on kind of, I don't remember the title of it,

00:16:40.760 --> 00:16:41.559
but it was sort of like,

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:45.239
this is how to use an information center.

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:50.119
And our utilization grew exponentially

00:16:50.119 --> 00:16:54.520
once folks knew how to ask us to ask a question,

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:55.400
if that makes sense.

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:00.039
To what degree do you have in your outreach program

00:17:00.039 --> 00:17:01.719
to the various lines of business,

00:17:01.719 --> 00:17:03.640
operations, marketing, HR,

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:06.599
all the functions that you mentioned a moment ago,

00:17:07.880 --> 00:17:09.079
anything like that,

00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:12.680
you know, to help them use you better.

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:14.439
That's my, that was my objective.

00:17:14.439 --> 00:17:17.560
I wanted to help my customers use us better.

00:17:18.199 --> 00:17:20.199
And to do that, one of the things I had to do

00:17:20.199 --> 00:17:23.479
is to give them a tool so they knew how to help,

00:17:23.479 --> 00:17:24.439
how to come to us.

00:17:25.079 --> 00:17:25.640
Your thoughts?

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:29.560
No, I have a lot of thoughts on that.

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:32.680
The thing I get excited about that, right,

00:17:32.680 --> 00:17:35.319
is that direct connection you pursued in doing that.

00:17:35.319 --> 00:17:38.199
I think that unlocks a lot if you can train

00:17:38.199 --> 00:17:40.199
and teach and create the patterns

00:17:40.199 --> 00:17:41.719
that actually work for them versus,

00:17:41.719 --> 00:17:43.640
you know, feed them what we think will work for them.

00:17:44.439 --> 00:17:45.640
I'd say on our side,

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:47.800
there's two things that stick out in our model

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:49.640
that maybe are a little unique.

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:53.239
One, we treat all of our models and science as products.

00:17:53.239 --> 00:17:55.239
So just as you would an application

00:17:55.239 --> 00:17:56.680
and treating it as a product

00:17:56.680 --> 00:17:58.599
and how what that user experience looks like

00:17:58.599 --> 00:18:01.079
and how you would build a roadmap around features

00:18:01.079 --> 00:18:02.439
and value and all of that,

00:18:02.439 --> 00:18:04.119
we do the same thing with our models.

00:18:04.119 --> 00:18:06.520
We want our users to have, you know,

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:08.839
some product accountability in terms of like,

00:18:08.839 --> 00:18:09.880
what is their experience?

00:18:09.880 --> 00:18:10.760
What's the outcomes?

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:11.719
How do we measure that?

00:18:11.719 --> 00:18:12.599
What does that look like?

00:18:12.599 --> 00:18:14.119
What's the efficacy of a model

00:18:14.119 --> 00:18:16.199
or what are we doing with it?

00:18:16.199 --> 00:18:18.680
And I think that that allows us

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:20.920
to also give them more support

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:22.920
as they engage with it and understand it

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:25.160
and also helps our scientists build a bridge

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:26.839
into like, hey, I want to go see this thing

00:18:26.839 --> 00:18:28.280
or let me go interview this user

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:29.400
or make a direct connection.

00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:30.439
You have it both ways.

00:18:31.319 --> 00:18:34.119
So I think one, having kind of product mindset

00:18:34.119 --> 00:18:35.400
and product connections

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:37.000
and governing and managing this stuff

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:39.800
takes more ownership in both of the outcomes

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:40.920
as well as what you're building.

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:42.599
So that's one.

00:18:42.599 --> 00:18:45.000
I'd say the other thing that we spend a lot of time on

00:18:45.800 --> 00:18:46.680
is that training.

00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:50.199
And so when we do the model,

00:18:50.199 --> 00:18:52.760
we spend a lot of time in training

00:18:52.760 --> 00:18:55.319
what the changes will look like in their systems

00:18:55.959 --> 00:18:57.560
or in the output of this.

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:00.920
On my screen is Alfredo.

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:04.839
He's on the team, but he's many times,

00:19:04.839 --> 00:19:07.239
I'm sure educated our stores partners on like,

00:19:07.239 --> 00:19:09.800
hey, this model will change what you see here.

00:19:10.359 --> 00:19:13.160
We will deliver not just the output of the model,

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:14.839
but the reports and the views

00:19:14.839 --> 00:19:15.719
and how they compare it

00:19:15.719 --> 00:19:17.800
and use it to all their other processes.

00:19:18.439 --> 00:19:19.640
And that's the way we can get

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:21.079
through change management and adoption

00:19:21.079 --> 00:19:23.160
a lot easier than we have in the past

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:25.079
where it's like, just give them the report

00:19:25.079 --> 00:19:26.199
and let them self-serve.

00:19:26.920 --> 00:19:28.359
I'd say it's much more high touch

00:19:28.359 --> 00:19:30.199
in making sure that they understand it

00:19:30.199 --> 00:19:31.640
and see those components come together.

00:19:33.319 --> 00:19:34.680
Oh, commendations, Fred.

00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:36.839
Sounds like you guys have a really good handle on it.

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:39.000
The one thing I really liked

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.319
from your remark or really stood out.

00:19:42.760 --> 00:19:44.040
I just want to make sure I jumped

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:45.160
to some of the other.

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:47.560
Yeah, it was the feedback loop.

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:50.520
So commendations and thank you, Rachel.

00:19:51.319 --> 00:19:52.680
I yield the floor.

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:55.239
No, thank you for the great questions.

00:19:55.239 --> 00:19:56.920
I just want to make sure I get to some here.

00:19:58.199 --> 00:20:00.439
But I really do love hearing

00:20:00.439 --> 00:20:03.239
about the immersion experience.

00:20:03.239 --> 00:20:05.319
And I remember when we were talking before,

00:20:05.400 --> 00:20:06.760
it was when you were planning

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:08.119
that trip out to California.

00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:12.359
I see Alan had a follow-up question on that.

00:20:12.359 --> 00:20:13.400
Alan, you want to jump in?

00:20:14.199 --> 00:20:15.000
Yeah, thanks.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:15.500
Hi, Brad.

00:20:16.199 --> 00:20:17.400
I'm really, really interested.

00:20:17.400 --> 00:20:19.800
I'm curious about how you sort of assess

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:21.160
things like physical impact.

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:22.119
You referred to that.

00:20:22.119 --> 00:20:24.599
Like, it sounds like, you know,

00:20:24.599 --> 00:20:26.520
seeing behavior changes in stores

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:28.599
or in customers or maybe in employees.

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:31.880
Really curious about how you measure that.

00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:33.160
It seems like a really interesting

00:20:33.160 --> 00:20:34.439
measurement question.

00:20:34.439 --> 00:20:36.040
And also, it seems like fieldwork,

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:37.400
which seems really fascinating

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:39.000
to do in that environment.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:40.199
So I wonder if there's anything

00:20:40.199 --> 00:20:41.640
you can sort of elaborate on there

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:43.959
about how you turn physical impact

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:46.040
into data that you can then

00:20:46.040 --> 00:20:47.479
continue to work with.

00:20:47.479 --> 00:20:49.560
Yes, so the feedback loop

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:50.760
we often look at, right,

00:20:50.760 --> 00:20:53.400
as a combination of all the virtual records

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:55.160
and events and the features

00:20:55.160 --> 00:20:56.199
that we train our model on

00:20:56.199 --> 00:20:57.880
and then score and then end up

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:58.839
giving us output.

00:20:58.839 --> 00:21:00.119
But we also look at, like,

00:21:00.119 --> 00:21:01.560
what are the business outcomes

00:21:01.560 --> 00:21:03.079
and measurements that

00:21:03.079 --> 00:21:04.199
subsequently follow?

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:06.599
We want to have effects and outcomes.

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:08.119
And that's how it turns

00:21:08.119 --> 00:21:09.640
into the value for Target.

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:11.160
And so an example I'll talk about

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:12.280
a little bit I can share.

00:21:12.839 --> 00:21:13.959
It's actually published

00:21:13.959 --> 00:21:15.640
in our Target blog, tech blog,

00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:17.079
if you want to go look at it.

00:21:17.079 --> 00:21:18.439
But we do something called

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:22.680
inventory corrections in our stores.

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:24.680
And so we use models

00:21:25.319 --> 00:21:27.800
that help us predict when something

00:21:28.359 --> 00:21:30.119
virtually is not there,

00:21:30.119 --> 00:21:31.000
even though physically

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:32.280
we think it is there.

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:33.800
And as we look at those events

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:34.439
in our stores,

00:21:34.439 --> 00:21:36.439
what we can see is different things

00:21:36.439 --> 00:21:37.880
subsequently happen.

00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:39.319
So we'll take a virtual record,

00:21:39.319 --> 00:21:40.680
we'll correct it.

00:21:40.680 --> 00:21:43.160
And then often tasks and workload

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:44.680
are generated from that.

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:45.560
And so then we'll see,

00:21:45.560 --> 00:21:46.520
did the team members

00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:48.119
go get the thing from the back room?

00:21:48.119 --> 00:21:49.160
Or did they find it?

00:21:49.160 --> 00:21:50.839
Or did subsequent other decisions

00:21:50.839 --> 00:21:52.359
in our systems change

00:21:52.359 --> 00:21:53.400
that then maybe brought

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:55.800
that item to the store?

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:56.839
And so we look at these

00:21:56.839 --> 00:21:57.880
physical connections

00:21:57.880 --> 00:21:59.000
and what that workload is,

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.359
what the effects are.

00:22:00.359 --> 00:22:02.119
Sometimes we make mistakes.

00:22:02.119 --> 00:22:03.239
And so we'll recommend

00:22:03.239 --> 00:22:05.319
something that's not there

00:22:05.319 --> 00:22:06.599
that actually is there.

00:22:06.599 --> 00:22:07.880
And then the team member will go

00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:09.560
actually do something with it.

00:22:09.560 --> 00:22:11.079
And then it doesn't fit on the floor,

00:22:11.079 --> 00:22:11.800
which then means

00:22:11.800 --> 00:22:12.839
they have rework to do.

00:22:12.839 --> 00:22:14.520
And that's a cost to target.

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:16.680
And it's a really frustrating experience

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:17.959
for the store team member.

00:22:17.959 --> 00:22:19.479
And so looking at not just the,

00:22:20.839 --> 00:22:22.439
you know, the precision of the model

00:22:22.439 --> 00:22:23.319
and the output

00:22:23.319 --> 00:22:25.079
and what value we're driving from that,

00:22:25.079 --> 00:22:27.239
but then the subsequent impacts of that

00:22:27.239 --> 00:22:28.760
has allowed us to connect back

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:29.880
and also build trust

00:22:30.599 --> 00:22:31.400
because we care more

00:22:31.400 --> 00:22:32.839
about the whole business problem

00:22:32.839 --> 00:22:33.959
than just even making,

00:22:33.959 --> 00:22:35.319
you know, those nuanced decisions

00:22:35.319 --> 00:22:37.719
better across the whole value stream.

00:22:37.719 --> 00:22:39.239
So that's a real example.

00:22:40.760 --> 00:22:41.880
Just to give you, you know,

00:22:41.880 --> 00:22:42.839
some scale on that,

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:44.599
you know, we do that hundreds

00:22:44.599 --> 00:22:46.280
of millions of times a week,

00:22:46.280 --> 00:22:47.640
which, you know, every team member

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:48.359
then has to touch

00:22:48.359 --> 00:22:49.640
those subsequent impacts.

00:22:49.640 --> 00:22:51.400
And it's fascinating

00:22:51.400 --> 00:22:52.599
to see this interaction

00:22:52.599 --> 00:22:54.599
and the costs and the interplay

00:22:54.599 --> 00:22:55.560
between the physical

00:22:55.560 --> 00:22:56.439
and virtual worlds.

00:22:57.640 --> 00:22:59.000
That's the really, really

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:00.040
like that at scale

00:23:00.040 --> 00:23:01.319
it's really interesting

00:23:01.319 --> 00:23:02.359
and impressive.

00:23:02.359 --> 00:23:03.000
Thank you.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:03.500
Thanks.

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:07.800
I see there's a few questions

00:23:07.800 --> 00:23:09.719
that came in about

00:23:09.719 --> 00:23:11.000
like sharing results

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:12.359
and reports with users.

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:15.079
I don't know if Jeb,

00:23:15.079 --> 00:23:15.719
you want to,

00:23:15.719 --> 00:23:17.160
oh, I see a star here

00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:17.880
so I can read it.

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:20.280
But the question was,

00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:22.680
how do you sell bad news?

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:23.800
We make data products

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:25.239
with sound bases

00:23:25.239 --> 00:23:27.560
and sometimes it surfaces issues

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:29.079
that might indicate an issue

00:23:29.079 --> 00:23:31.319
or concern more often

00:23:31.319 --> 00:23:32.359
than I want to admit.

00:23:32.359 --> 00:23:33.800
There's pushback on the model

00:23:33.800 --> 00:23:35.400
rather than a look at the issue.

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:39.000
A real life example of that

00:23:40.439 --> 00:23:43.000
is highlighted often in simulation.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:44.839
So we'll use and work

00:23:44.839 --> 00:23:46.839
across business teams.

00:23:46.839 --> 00:23:48.680
And recently,

00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:49.959
some of you guys probably know

00:23:49.959 --> 00:23:51.319
Target rolled out Starbucks

00:23:51.880 --> 00:23:53.079
as part of your drive up order.

00:23:54.119 --> 00:23:55.319
If you shop at Target,

00:23:55.319 --> 00:23:56.760
it's an amazing benefit

00:23:56.760 --> 00:23:57.400
because you can get

00:23:57.400 --> 00:23:58.359
your Starbucks in your car

00:23:58.359 --> 00:23:59.239
while you're also waiting

00:23:59.239 --> 00:23:59.959
for your groceries

00:23:59.959 --> 00:24:01.000
or anything else.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:01.880
I'm a big fan.

00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:03.959
But as we were looking at

00:24:03.959 --> 00:24:04.839
and modeling out,

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:07.479
actually simulating that for stores

00:24:07.479 --> 00:24:08.680
and the work there,

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:10.680
what we found is the data

00:24:10.680 --> 00:24:11.959
told a different story

00:24:11.959 --> 00:24:14.520
than what our subject matter experts

00:24:14.520 --> 00:24:16.439
at headquarters expected to happen

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:19.000
when team members or payroll

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:20.119
was being used in stores.

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:21.640
And I, you know,

00:24:22.839 --> 00:24:24.359
that wasn't a great story

00:24:24.359 --> 00:24:25.560
to be like, sorry,

00:24:25.560 --> 00:24:26.680
I know your process

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:27.880
is defined this way

00:24:27.959 --> 00:24:29.160
and you expect all of this

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:30.119
to happen in this way,

00:24:30.119 --> 00:24:31.400
but you're wrong.

00:24:32.839 --> 00:24:33.880
But I think the reality

00:24:33.880 --> 00:24:35.400
is we met them there.

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:36.599
We showed them the physical.

00:24:36.599 --> 00:24:39.560
We actually met with them in stores.

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:41.560
We walked through the virtual records,

00:24:41.560 --> 00:24:44.280
the physical actions and activities.

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:45.719
We saw these things

00:24:45.719 --> 00:24:46.920
changing and evolving.

00:24:47.479 --> 00:24:49.079
And what happened

00:24:49.079 --> 00:24:50.359
is we drew alignment

00:24:50.359 --> 00:24:51.319
between the physical

00:24:51.319 --> 00:24:52.119
and the virtual

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:53.800
and highlighted those,

00:24:54.439 --> 00:24:55.560
I'd say perceptions

00:24:55.560 --> 00:24:56.920
that were incorrect

00:24:56.920 --> 00:24:58.280
and allowed data to kind of work

00:24:58.280 --> 00:24:59.400
and tell the story.

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:01.479
And so, yes, it was bad news.

00:25:01.479 --> 00:25:02.599
But I think at the end,

00:25:02.599 --> 00:25:04.359
because we were all aligned

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:06.280
and doing that work together,

00:25:06.839 --> 00:25:08.040
we were able to deliver it

00:25:08.040 --> 00:25:09.479
with some empathy and connection,

00:25:09.479 --> 00:25:11.319
which ultimately led to us

00:25:11.319 --> 00:25:12.920
advancing the overall solution

00:25:12.920 --> 00:25:14.839
and simulation for our stores,

00:25:14.839 --> 00:25:15.400
which helped them

00:25:15.400 --> 00:25:16.760
transform other decisions.

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:17.880
And so they saw it

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:19.640
not just as a serving bad news,

00:25:19.640 --> 00:25:20.599
but being a partner

00:25:20.599 --> 00:25:22.359
and then unlocking other capabilities

00:25:22.359 --> 00:25:23.400
that advanced it further.

00:25:25.079 --> 00:25:25.959
That's a real example.

00:25:27.719 --> 00:25:29.239
Thank you.

00:25:29.800 --> 00:25:31.640
I am thinking,

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:32.680
like, as we're talking about

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:34.520
watching people in the physical stores,

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:36.040
like, how does that translate

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:38.280
over to the website to

00:25:38.280 --> 00:25:40.599
or like knowing the process

00:25:40.599 --> 00:25:41.400
people are going through

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:42.199
to find things?

00:25:43.719 --> 00:25:45.479
Yeah, we, I think,

00:25:45.479 --> 00:25:46.439
have a great desire

00:25:46.439 --> 00:25:47.800
to be more sophisticated

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:48.520
of blending,

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:50.119
like our digital experience

00:25:50.119 --> 00:25:51.160
with everything else

00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:52.359
in the physical operations.

00:25:54.199 --> 00:25:56.199
If you have read in the news

00:25:56.199 --> 00:25:57.239
the last couple of quarters,

00:25:57.239 --> 00:25:59.319
our digital sales and things

00:25:59.319 --> 00:26:00.599
have taken a little bit of a hit.

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:03.640
I'd say overall, though,

00:26:03.640 --> 00:26:05.319
Target's been well-positioned

00:26:05.319 --> 00:26:07.640
to try to be a great place

00:26:07.640 --> 00:26:08.839
to shop and meet our guests

00:26:08.839 --> 00:26:09.800
with the demands they have.

00:26:09.800 --> 00:26:10.680
We've, you know,

00:26:10.680 --> 00:26:11.560
through the pandemic,

00:26:11.560 --> 00:26:12.439
opened up drive up,

00:26:12.439 --> 00:26:13.800
pick up and all their services.

00:26:14.359 --> 00:26:16.439
But that doesn't always fit

00:26:16.439 --> 00:26:18.680
within the same guest experience

00:26:18.680 --> 00:26:19.719
as you have if you were

00:26:19.719 --> 00:26:21.560
just to shop one of our stores.

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:22.920
You always can see the buzz

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:24.359
of somebody having a lot of fun

00:26:24.359 --> 00:26:25.719
at a Target store.

00:26:25.800 --> 00:26:27.319
But we don't often get

00:26:27.319 --> 00:26:28.599
the same experience digitally.

00:26:28.599 --> 00:26:29.959
And so it's a huge effort for us

00:26:29.959 --> 00:26:31.800
to start to sync up on these things,

00:26:32.359 --> 00:26:33.880
you know, make search better,

00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.839
make recommendations clearer,

00:26:36.839 --> 00:26:38.040
you know, compete on some

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:39.800
of those digital experience things

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:40.839
that, you know,

00:26:40.839 --> 00:26:42.359
you can browse and shop

00:26:42.359 --> 00:26:43.880
in a store that Target's known for

00:26:43.880 --> 00:26:45.400
that we haven't completely

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:46.199
been able to do.

00:26:46.199 --> 00:26:47.719
But I think we're on that journey.

00:26:48.359 --> 00:26:49.479
And, you know,

00:26:49.479 --> 00:26:51.160
our services and operations

00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:52.199
in the space that I know,

00:26:52.199 --> 00:26:53.959
we are truly trying to sync that up

00:26:53.959 --> 00:26:54.920
as much as possible

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:56.680
to make that as easy as possible.

00:26:56.680 --> 00:26:58.439
So the dynamics of you shopping

00:26:58.439 --> 00:26:59.959
with ease and checkout with ease

00:26:59.959 --> 00:27:01.640
should be as easily as you are

00:27:01.640 --> 00:27:02.920
as easy as your store

00:27:02.920 --> 00:27:04.199
walking through a checkout line

00:27:04.199 --> 00:27:06.040
as it can be digitally.

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:07.479
And I think those are just nuances

00:27:07.479 --> 00:27:08.520
of try to try to blend

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:09.959
those two experiences together.

00:27:12.119 --> 00:27:13.000
Thank you.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.439
I see a few people commenting

00:27:14.439 --> 00:27:17.000
in the chat that used to work at Target

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:18.119
and love hearing those

00:27:18.119 --> 00:27:19.400
behind the scenes here too.

00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:22.680
Abigail, I see you had a question.

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:23.560
Want to jump in next?

00:27:24.920 --> 00:27:25.420
Hi.

00:27:25.959 --> 00:27:27.319
So increasingly, as I get to be

00:27:27.319 --> 00:27:28.439
like an old person,

00:27:28.439 --> 00:27:29.479
people send me their resumes

00:27:29.479 --> 00:27:30.599
and they ask me for advice

00:27:31.319 --> 00:27:32.199
and I give them advice,

00:27:32.199 --> 00:27:33.079
but it's hard for me to tell

00:27:33.079 --> 00:27:33.880
how much of my advice

00:27:33.880 --> 00:27:35.319
is completely idiosyncratic.

00:27:36.280 --> 00:27:37.400
So like, yeah,

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:38.040
like when you're looking

00:27:38.040 --> 00:27:38.920
for junior people,

00:27:38.920 --> 00:27:39.800
like what do you look for?

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:40.760
What do you assess?

00:27:40.760 --> 00:27:42.359
What are your metrics?

00:27:42.359 --> 00:27:42.859
Whatever.

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:46.040
Yeah, I'd say the biggest thing,

00:27:46.040 --> 00:27:47.640
regardless of what's on the resume

00:27:47.640 --> 00:27:50.199
or experience is just the curiosity

00:27:50.199 --> 00:27:51.800
and willingness to go experiment

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:52.520
and do new things.

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:56.439
This space has changed so much

00:27:56.439 --> 00:27:57.319
and it's going to continue

00:27:57.319 --> 00:27:58.439
to change so rapidly.

00:27:59.079 --> 00:28:00.839
Their willingness to learn,

00:28:02.119 --> 00:28:03.800
to dive in with curiosity,

00:28:03.800 --> 00:28:05.560
build and connect and work with peers.

00:28:06.119 --> 00:28:08.760
The one thing I really,

00:28:08.760 --> 00:28:09.719
that's kept me at Target

00:28:09.719 --> 00:28:10.280
as long as it has,

00:28:10.280 --> 00:28:11.880
is the diversity of talent around me.

00:28:12.520 --> 00:28:14.119
And so I think their ability

00:28:14.119 --> 00:28:15.239
to be curious

00:28:15.239 --> 00:28:16.520
and then reach out to people

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:17.479
and work with others

00:28:17.479 --> 00:28:19.400
and pull in diverse perspectives.

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:20.599
Those are the things I'm often

00:28:20.599 --> 00:28:22.280
asking about in interviews.

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:23.560
That differentiates somebody

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:25.319
from what's just on their resume.

00:28:25.319 --> 00:28:27.719
And so I think that type of,

00:28:27.719 --> 00:28:29.000
however you can show that

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:30.520
in terms of your experience

00:28:30.520 --> 00:28:32.280
or the projects you work on

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:34.439
or the type of products,

00:28:34.439 --> 00:28:36.119
models, things you're building,

00:28:36.119 --> 00:28:38.040
I think that just goes such a long way.

00:28:38.839 --> 00:28:39.640
Because rarely are you

00:28:39.640 --> 00:28:40.680
just doing it yourself

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:41.959
and rarely are you the one

00:28:41.959 --> 00:28:44.199
who's done the initial research,

00:28:44.199 --> 00:28:45.160
algorithm development

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:46.040
or model development

00:28:46.040 --> 00:28:47.560
that was published originally.

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:49.000
At least I don't see that at Target.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:50.520
I mean, I'm sure some of the bigger

00:28:50.520 --> 00:28:51.560
tech organizations,

00:28:52.280 --> 00:28:53.719
you know, transforming the world.

00:28:53.719 --> 00:28:54.839
But I think there's a lot of

00:28:54.839 --> 00:28:56.119
just how do you, you know,

00:28:56.119 --> 00:28:57.400
do more of the applied side

00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:58.359
and work with teams

00:28:58.359 --> 00:29:00.439
and dive in to solve real problems.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:05.500
Thank you.

00:29:06.439 --> 00:29:08.199
Adam, I see you had a question

00:29:08.199 --> 00:29:10.280
earlier on model governance.

00:29:10.839 --> 00:29:12.119
Want to ask that now?

00:29:12.119 --> 00:29:13.560
Yeah, just going back

00:29:13.560 --> 00:29:14.599
to the earlier conversation

00:29:15.239 --> 00:29:16.680
about that one anecdote

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:19.959
that shall not be named.

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:21.560
I'm curious about,

00:29:21.560 --> 00:29:22.359
you kind of mentioned like,

00:29:22.359 --> 00:29:22.760
well, you know,

00:29:22.760 --> 00:29:23.800
we didn't really have good

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:25.319
model governance practices and things.

00:29:25.319 --> 00:29:26.839
I'm curious sort of like

00:29:26.839 --> 00:29:27.959
what the evolution of that

00:29:27.959 --> 00:29:28.599
has looked like

00:29:29.319 --> 00:29:30.439
if you're able to share

00:29:30.439 --> 00:29:31.719
how models get validated

00:29:31.719 --> 00:29:33.479
or reviewed for correctness or bias.

00:29:34.119 --> 00:29:34.680
And then, you know,

00:29:34.680 --> 00:29:35.719
is that team sort of separate

00:29:35.719 --> 00:29:36.760
or is all kind of like

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:38.920
in-house within data science?

00:29:39.719 --> 00:29:40.920
No, it's all in-house.

00:29:40.920 --> 00:29:42.439
I would love to say

00:29:42.439 --> 00:29:44.439
we have built this full

00:29:44.439 --> 00:29:46.359
like MLOps ecosystem out

00:29:46.359 --> 00:29:47.319
and we have, you know,

00:29:47.319 --> 00:29:49.079
some unbiased ways of measuring,

00:29:49.160 --> 00:29:50.119
scoring, doing all of that.

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:52.520
I would say we do a much better

00:29:52.520 --> 00:29:53.560
job than we've ever done.

00:29:53.560 --> 00:29:55.479
We do have a data governance team

00:29:55.479 --> 00:29:56.599
that helps us at least

00:29:56.599 --> 00:29:57.719
with the data pieces

00:29:57.719 --> 00:29:59.319
and making sure, you know,

00:29:59.319 --> 00:30:00.280
what people are using

00:30:00.280 --> 00:30:01.880
and consuming as features

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:04.280
and things are much more controlled

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:05.160
than they've ever been.

00:30:06.040 --> 00:30:06.839
But as we think about

00:30:06.839 --> 00:30:08.839
like model scoring and the outputs,

00:30:08.839 --> 00:30:10.680
like we do that individually.

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:13.000
We often work within our teams

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:14.280
to do the reviews.

00:30:15.479 --> 00:30:16.439
And I think sometimes

00:30:16.439 --> 00:30:17.800
that's good enough.

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:19.000
But I think there's a lot of times

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:19.800
where we could do better.

00:30:20.359 --> 00:30:21.479
And, you know, that's something

00:30:21.479 --> 00:30:23.079
that's top of mind for Target,

00:30:23.079 --> 00:30:24.520
top of mind for where we're going

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:27.000
with the future of our science platforms,

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:28.680
where a lot of those things are,

00:30:28.680 --> 00:30:30.680
you know, in our desired end state

00:30:30.680 --> 00:30:33.479
is built right into the patterns

00:30:33.479 --> 00:30:34.920
and processes that we're following

00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:36.119
as scientists.

00:30:36.119 --> 00:30:37.479
And so we're on a journey to do that.

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:41.160
I'd say our tooling,

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:42.599
for those who maybe don't know Target,

00:30:42.599 --> 00:30:43.719
all of our internal tooling

00:30:43.719 --> 00:30:45.000
is almost all in-house,

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:45.800
open source built.

00:30:46.359 --> 00:30:48.439
And so a lot of what it takes

00:30:48.439 --> 00:30:50.520
to stand that up is a combination

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:52.040
of just the right engineering partners,

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:53.160
the right scientists,

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:54.520
and, you know, honestly,

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:55.880
even the right leadership

00:30:55.880 --> 00:30:56.920
to build that governance

00:30:56.920 --> 00:30:57.880
and controls across.

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:00.199
And we are committed to doing that,

00:31:00.199 --> 00:31:01.079
but it is a journey

00:31:01.079 --> 00:31:02.280
and it's going to continue to evolve.

00:31:02.280 --> 00:31:03.719
Yeah.

00:31:03.719 --> 00:31:04.520
And you're not behind.

00:31:04.520 --> 00:31:05.800
I mean, I think every business

00:31:05.800 --> 00:31:08.040
is really giving deep thought right now

00:31:08.040 --> 00:31:09.000
about how they go about that.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:10.359
So thanks for sharing.

00:31:10.359 --> 00:31:10.920
Yeah, of course.

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:14.439
Funday, I see you had a question

00:31:14.439 --> 00:31:15.640
a bit earlier as well

00:31:16.439 --> 00:31:18.680
on working with decision makers.

00:31:18.680 --> 00:31:19.400
Want to jump in?

00:31:20.680 --> 00:31:21.560
Yeah, thanks.

00:31:21.560 --> 00:31:22.280
Great talk so far.

00:31:23.400 --> 00:31:24.839
Yeah, I'm just thinking

00:31:25.719 --> 00:31:28.040
this is something I get to encounter

00:31:28.040 --> 00:31:28.839
every now and then.

00:31:28.839 --> 00:31:31.479
You have people who are supposed

00:31:31.479 --> 00:31:33.000
to be senior level

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:34.119
and make, you know,

00:31:34.119 --> 00:31:35.640
all these huge decisions.

00:31:35.640 --> 00:31:36.839
And they have this way

00:31:36.839 --> 00:31:37.800
of sounding really smart

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:39.160
when they have all these nice plots

00:31:39.160 --> 00:31:39.959
and charts and graphs

00:31:39.959 --> 00:31:40.839
and stuff in front of them

00:31:40.839 --> 00:31:41.880
that has been prepared

00:31:41.880 --> 00:31:42.839
and all laid out.

00:31:43.479 --> 00:31:44.680
And yeah, they sound smart.

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:46.599
But when you listen carefully enough,

00:31:46.599 --> 00:31:48.839
you sense they don't quite

00:31:48.839 --> 00:31:49.800
get what's going on,

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:53.479
you know, and it plays out in decision.

00:31:53.479 --> 00:31:54.839
Sometimes you have to show up again

00:31:54.839 --> 00:31:55.800
and explain, you know,

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:57.560
what this actually meant was,

00:31:58.680 --> 00:31:59.180
you know.

00:31:59.880 --> 00:32:03.479
So if you were to pick one area,

00:32:03.479 --> 00:32:05.800
you'd say you could help improve,

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:07.880
like offer some kind of training for,

00:32:08.680 --> 00:32:10.199
you know, and this is not trying

00:32:10.199 --> 00:32:11.560
to make everyone a data scientist,

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:12.599
you know, say, let's say,

00:32:13.239 --> 00:32:14.439
conceptual understanding

00:32:14.439 --> 00:32:16.040
of maybe probability theory

00:32:16.040 --> 00:32:18.760
or, you know, one thing,

00:32:18.760 --> 00:32:19.800
if there was one area,

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:22.680
you'd say high level conceptual

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:24.439
that they could benefit from

00:32:24.439 --> 00:32:25.640
to help them understand

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:27.319
this thing, these things better.

00:32:27.319 --> 00:32:27.959
What would it be?

00:32:29.400 --> 00:32:30.920
That's a really good question.

00:32:33.319 --> 00:32:34.199
I'll start probably

00:32:34.199 --> 00:32:35.479
even more simplistic.

00:32:35.479 --> 00:32:37.239
Like, I think the biggest thing

00:32:37.239 --> 00:32:39.319
I preach to most of

00:32:39.959 --> 00:32:41.319
my business partners

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:42.839
and even team is,

00:32:43.400 --> 00:32:45.079
do you understand the inputs

00:32:45.079 --> 00:32:46.439
that are affecting your outputs?

00:32:47.319 --> 00:32:50.119
And do you really understand

00:32:50.119 --> 00:32:51.880
what went into those decisions

00:32:51.880 --> 00:32:54.040
or those variables that led to,

00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:56.439
you know, the other models

00:32:56.439 --> 00:32:58.119
or algorithms or all of that?

00:32:58.119 --> 00:32:59.319
And most of the time,

00:32:59.319 --> 00:33:02.439
what I find is a lot of hypotheses

00:33:03.079 --> 00:33:04.920
on what happened within those inputs.

00:33:04.920 --> 00:33:07.319
Well, somebody else owned that

00:33:07.319 --> 00:33:08.680
or somebody else knew that

00:33:08.680 --> 00:33:10.040
or that was already decided

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:11.000
and I can't change it.

00:33:11.560 --> 00:33:12.599
And in reality,

00:33:12.599 --> 00:33:13.959
there's so much of just,

00:33:13.959 --> 00:33:15.400
can you affect the inputs

00:33:15.400 --> 00:33:16.680
instead of just changing

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:18.359
or overriding or,

00:33:18.359 --> 00:33:20.199
you know, biasing in between

00:33:20.199 --> 00:33:21.479
what you want to have happen?

00:33:22.040 --> 00:33:23.319
That I think it starts with,

00:33:23.319 --> 00:33:24.439
do you take the time

00:33:24.439 --> 00:33:25.800
to understand those effects

00:33:26.839 --> 00:33:28.359
of what happened upstream of you?

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:30.520
Which regardless of science,

00:33:30.520 --> 00:33:32.599
I think is a really good behavior.

00:33:32.599 --> 00:33:35.079
If I start with just what has happened

00:33:35.079 --> 00:33:36.119
before I ended up

00:33:36.119 --> 00:33:37.400
having to make this decision

00:33:37.400 --> 00:33:39.079
or what I'm dealing with right now,

00:33:39.640 --> 00:33:42.359
I can usually start with a point of,

00:33:42.359 --> 00:33:43.800
I've used the word empathy a couple of times,

00:33:43.800 --> 00:33:44.599
but I usually start

00:33:44.599 --> 00:33:45.800
with a point of empathy to say,

00:33:45.800 --> 00:33:46.760
what did they deal with?

00:33:47.479 --> 00:33:49.479
What was constrained for them?

00:33:49.479 --> 00:33:50.359
What were variables

00:33:50.359 --> 00:33:51.560
that they weren't able to consider?

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:53.479
What was the data they didn't have?

00:33:53.479 --> 00:33:54.599
And then I can work back

00:33:54.599 --> 00:33:56.359
even to their inputs and say,

00:33:56.359 --> 00:33:58.280
wow, if I actually change this other thing

00:33:58.280 --> 00:34:00.520
or help them understand that other thing,

00:34:00.520 --> 00:34:02.680
the effects all the way through this

00:34:02.680 --> 00:34:04.199
can be changed as well.

00:34:04.199 --> 00:34:05.160
And so that, I mean,

00:34:05.160 --> 00:34:06.199
fundamentally I think

00:34:06.199 --> 00:34:08.520
is just a foundational building block

00:34:08.520 --> 00:34:10.439
for anybody in science

00:34:10.439 --> 00:34:11.719
or operations or whatever

00:34:11.719 --> 00:34:12.840
that I think is really important.

00:34:12.840 --> 00:34:15.399
Yeah, just real quickly.

00:34:15.399 --> 00:34:16.679
And the last thing is,

00:34:16.679 --> 00:34:18.520
you know, if you could pick between,

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:22.280
let's say, understanding bias,

00:34:22.280 --> 00:34:24.120
for example, you know,

00:34:24.120 --> 00:34:26.760
or, you know, because very often

00:34:26.760 --> 00:34:27.959
people don't get it when you say,

00:34:27.959 --> 00:34:28.840
these are the limitations

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:29.959
or these are the things

00:34:29.959 --> 00:34:30.600
you should consider.

00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:31.800
They just go like, hey,

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:32.520
this is the answer.

00:34:32.520 --> 00:34:33.479
And then you go for it.

00:34:33.479 --> 00:34:35.239
You know, just one area,

00:34:35.239 --> 00:34:36.840
just one area, you'd say.

00:34:37.479 --> 00:34:39.639
I would just ask, you know, why?

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:40.760
Why is this a problem?

00:34:40.760 --> 00:34:43.159
Like, you know, I think asking that

00:34:43.159 --> 00:34:44.760
why and understanding it,

00:34:44.760 --> 00:34:45.879
there's oftentimes where people

00:34:45.879 --> 00:34:47.080
will come to us with problems like,

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:48.520
we need data science to do this.

00:34:49.159 --> 00:34:50.280
And when you ask why

00:34:50.280 --> 00:34:51.719
and then you ask them to define it,

00:34:52.360 --> 00:34:53.320
sometimes it's not even

00:34:53.320 --> 00:34:55.719
a data science problem, right?

00:34:55.719 --> 00:34:59.239
Like you need a binary decision,

00:34:59.239 --> 00:35:00.199
you know, and sometimes

00:35:00.199 --> 00:35:02.199
like we can help you build that,

00:35:02.199 --> 00:35:03.479
like we can do that.

00:35:03.479 --> 00:35:04.600
But like that doesn't take

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:05.639
any data science model.

00:35:06.919 --> 00:35:08.520
And so I think asking the why

00:35:08.520 --> 00:35:09.479
and then digging into like,

00:35:09.479 --> 00:35:11.000
what do you really want to accomplish?

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:12.360
Sometimes you can really simplify

00:35:12.360 --> 00:35:13.479
the solution without even

00:35:13.479 --> 00:35:14.439
having to do the work.

