00:40:36.439 --> 00:40:38.120
if what kind of modeling techniques

00:40:38.120 --> 00:40:38.679
you're using,

00:40:39.320 --> 00:40:40.360
whether it's mixed integer

00:40:40.360 --> 00:40:41.239
programming or

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:43.159
different things like that

00:40:43.159 --> 00:40:44.360
to solve some of these

00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:45.560
supply chain problems.

00:40:47.320 --> 00:40:48.840
Mainly kind of around

00:40:49.800 --> 00:40:51.800
making sure that your production

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:52.760
or not production, but

00:40:53.719 --> 00:40:55.000
outbound operations

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:56.199
from a supply chain center

00:40:56.199 --> 00:40:59.560
can adequately supply

00:40:59.639 --> 00:41:00.760
your target stores.

00:41:01.719 --> 00:41:02.360
Yeah, we do.

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:03.080
We have several

00:41:03.080 --> 00:41:04.120
different optimizations

00:41:04.120 --> 00:41:05.879
that we run all across

00:41:05.879 --> 00:41:07.399
from mixed integer programs

00:41:07.399 --> 00:41:08.520
to linear programs

00:41:08.520 --> 00:41:12.040
to just various

00:41:12.040 --> 00:41:13.239
optimization techniques.

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:17.159
We try to synchronize

00:41:17.159 --> 00:41:18.520
those as much as possible

00:41:18.520 --> 00:41:20.919
and even simulating the variables

00:41:20.919 --> 00:41:22.360
and what those optimizations

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:23.320
are up and downstream.

00:41:23.320 --> 00:41:24.840
So as we think about,

00:41:25.879 --> 00:41:27.080
well, just an example,

00:41:27.639 --> 00:41:29.800
we have a state of inventory.

00:41:29.800 --> 00:41:31.080
And as we think about that state

00:41:31.800 --> 00:41:32.840
moving throughout,

00:41:33.399 --> 00:41:34.360
the optimization

00:41:34.360 --> 00:41:35.560
is making those decisions

00:41:35.560 --> 00:41:37.080
and we can use those

00:41:37.080 --> 00:41:38.919
different optimization engines

00:41:38.919 --> 00:41:39.959
to simulate variables

00:41:39.959 --> 00:41:40.760
up and downstream.

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:41.639
And so we feed

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:45.080
stochastic inputs into those

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:46.120
and then derive

00:41:47.239 --> 00:41:48.600
different outcomes from that,

00:41:48.600 --> 00:41:50.280
which give us scenarios.

00:41:50.280 --> 00:41:51.320
And then those scenarios

00:41:51.320 --> 00:41:52.679
bias what gets input again.

00:41:52.679 --> 00:41:54.199
And so we use that

00:41:54.199 --> 00:41:56.439
from purchasing to positioning

00:41:56.439 --> 00:41:57.959
to what gets placed in a store

00:41:57.959 --> 00:41:59.320
to what gets replenished.

00:42:00.199 --> 00:42:01.239
And those variables

00:42:01.239 --> 00:42:03.159
are all then built across

00:42:03.159 --> 00:42:05.320
and we maintain that holistically.

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:06.439
And so it's a, you know,

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.399
if you were to build it overall, right?

00:42:09.399 --> 00:42:10.439
Like you could think about it

00:42:10.439 --> 00:42:13.239
being one big mixed integer program

00:42:13.239 --> 00:42:13.959
all the way through

00:42:14.840 --> 00:42:15.560
the reality of that

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:16.600
as we build the components

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:17.479
in the building blocks

00:42:17.479 --> 00:42:18.760
and then try to share states

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:20.600
as we maximize

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:21.879
or minimize different functions.

00:42:25.159 --> 00:42:25.719
Very cool.

