00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:38.840
Yeah, I love to start.

00:54:39.399 --> 00:54:40.760
Maybe this is because I've spent

00:54:40.760 --> 00:54:41.800
time in supply chain,

00:54:41.800 --> 00:54:43.399
but I really think fundamentally

00:54:43.399 --> 00:54:44.439
starting with the steps

00:54:44.439 --> 00:54:46.360
of problem definition

00:54:46.360 --> 00:54:48.439
and breakdown allows you

00:54:48.439 --> 00:54:50.040
to then help build a bridge

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:51.239
of like what data actually

00:54:51.239 --> 00:54:52.439
helps you solve that problem.

00:54:53.959 --> 00:54:57.000
It removes the assumptions

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:58.679
on the data will tell the future

00:54:58.679 --> 00:54:59.879
or the data will help us

00:54:59.879 --> 00:55:01.320
change this or that.

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:02.360
And I think when you just start

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:03.639
to break down, we talked

00:55:03.719 --> 00:55:04.439
a little bit about the why,

00:55:04.439 --> 00:55:05.560
but when you start to break down,

00:55:05.560 --> 00:55:08.280
you're trying to get to this point.

00:55:08.280 --> 00:55:09.399
You want to understand this.

00:55:09.399 --> 00:55:10.600
And then you look at,

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:12.280
maybe it's the defects that caused it,

00:55:12.280 --> 00:55:14.439
or maybe it's the changes

00:55:14.439 --> 00:55:15.399
in upstream decisions

00:55:15.399 --> 00:55:16.280
that impacted it,

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:19.159
or maybe it's external factors,

00:55:19.719 --> 00:55:21.560
guest experiences, demand shifts,

00:55:21.560 --> 00:55:22.439
whatever it might be.

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:24.439
I think when you start to break down

00:55:24.439 --> 00:55:25.719
the problems in ways

00:55:25.719 --> 00:55:27.320
that they can tangibly see and fit,

00:55:27.320 --> 00:55:29.320
then you can also meet them in that,

00:55:29.320 --> 00:55:30.760
which allows you to communicate

00:55:30.760 --> 00:55:32.600
how the data fits the problem as well.

00:55:34.600 --> 00:55:38.360
How, and just leaning

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:40.520
into the communication topic a bit more,

00:55:41.959 --> 00:55:44.760
how do you teach communication

00:55:44.760 --> 00:55:47.000
to somebody new on your team?

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:48.679
Do you have any strategies for that?

00:55:49.719 --> 00:55:52.360
Lots of practice, right?

00:55:52.360 --> 00:55:53.719
I talk about the immersion experience

00:55:53.719 --> 00:55:55.959
for my leaders, but that,

00:55:55.959 --> 00:55:57.159
you know, when I talk about leaders,

00:55:57.159 --> 00:55:58.840
we have principals who are,

00:55:58.840 --> 00:56:00.760
you know, mostly PhDs,

00:56:00.760 --> 00:56:02.520
deep technical experts.

00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:04.040
I also consider them leaders.

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:05.959
They don't have any DRs,

00:56:05.959 --> 00:56:08.280
but they're leading the technical vision,

00:56:08.280 --> 00:56:09.879
architecture frameworks,

00:56:09.879 --> 00:56:11.399
you know, practices that we do.

00:56:11.399 --> 00:56:13.399
And then our leaders, our directors,

00:56:14.280 --> 00:56:15.479
and I think equally the way

00:56:15.479 --> 00:56:16.919
they communicate and engage

00:56:16.919 --> 00:56:17.879
is super important.

00:56:17.879 --> 00:56:19.000
And so I think the best thing

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:20.520
is practice and exposure

00:56:21.159 --> 00:56:22.199
and coming alongside

00:56:22.199 --> 00:56:23.479
as we think about what we're doing

00:56:23.479 --> 00:56:24.520
and who we're sharing with.

00:56:24.520 --> 00:56:25.560
So know your audience

00:56:26.280 --> 00:56:27.479
and then practice with them.

00:56:30.360 --> 00:56:32.120
So maybe one last question

00:56:32.439 --> 00:56:34.520
before we all have to drop,

00:56:34.520 --> 00:56:37.320
unfortunately, is just thinking

00:56:37.320 --> 00:56:39.159
about like all the ideas

00:56:39.159 --> 00:56:41.399
that your team comes up with

00:56:41.399 --> 00:56:43.239
or just new ways of looking at data.

00:56:43.239 --> 00:56:46.120
How do you go about sharing ideas

00:56:46.120 --> 00:56:48.040
or deciding what to work on next?

00:56:51.080 --> 00:56:52.199
Yeah, there's a couple of things.

00:56:52.199 --> 00:56:53.959
So I talked about us being on a journey

00:56:53.959 --> 00:56:55.879
to experiment and moving faster.

00:56:55.879 --> 00:56:57.560
We have something at Target

00:56:57.560 --> 00:56:58.919
called our 50 days of learning.

00:56:58.919 --> 00:57:01.080
And so we make sure our teams

00:57:01.159 --> 00:57:02.600
have the space.

00:57:02.600 --> 00:57:04.439
If you think about 50 days in a year,

00:57:04.439 --> 00:57:05.959
it's 20% of your time.

00:57:05.959 --> 00:57:07.399
We try to make sure the team

00:57:07.399 --> 00:57:09.639
has that space to explore new ideas

00:57:09.639 --> 00:57:11.719
and also look at, you know,

00:57:11.719 --> 00:57:13.560
sharing ideas across the organization

00:57:13.560 --> 00:57:14.760
and sponsoring those things.

00:57:14.760 --> 00:57:16.439
So, you know, if you're in,

00:57:16.439 --> 00:57:17.879
you know, my team on the OR side,

00:57:17.879 --> 00:57:18.760
but you want to work on

00:57:18.760 --> 00:57:20.679
maybe more of a deep learning project

00:57:20.679 --> 00:57:22.040
or something like that,

00:57:22.040 --> 00:57:23.479
we'll use that 50 days of learning

00:57:23.479 --> 00:57:25.000
to have somebody go get experience

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:26.439
in recommendation systems

00:57:26.439 --> 00:57:28.439
or in search or some other things like that.

00:57:28.439 --> 00:57:30.199
And I think that's one unique way

00:57:30.199 --> 00:57:30.760
we do it.

00:57:31.479 --> 00:57:32.280
But then also I talked

00:57:32.280 --> 00:57:33.239
about the product model.

00:57:33.239 --> 00:57:34.360
I think the product model

00:57:34.360 --> 00:57:35.479
and having that business

00:57:35.479 --> 00:57:37.000
partnership and expertise

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:38.840
allows you to also index on the value

00:57:38.840 --> 00:57:40.760
that your team is working against.

00:57:40.760 --> 00:57:42.679
And so the more value you unlock,

00:57:42.679 --> 00:57:43.719
the more investment you get,

00:57:43.719 --> 00:57:45.000
the more creative and space

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:46.679
you get to go work on those unique,

00:57:46.679 --> 00:57:49.000
exciting problems and research as well.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:50.360
And so I think when you blend

00:57:50.360 --> 00:57:51.719
that empathy and connection

00:57:51.719 --> 00:57:53.320
to the value they want to unlock,

00:57:53.320 --> 00:57:55.159
as well as your curiosity

00:57:55.159 --> 00:57:56.280
and connection to the team,

00:57:56.280 --> 00:57:57.159
you end up being able

00:57:57.159 --> 00:57:59.399
to do more independently too.

00:58:01.080 --> 00:58:01.800
Absolutely.

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:03.239
Thank you so much, Brad,

00:58:03.239 --> 00:58:05.479
for taking the time to join us today

00:58:05.479 --> 00:58:07.159
and sharing your experience.

00:58:07.719 --> 00:58:09.159
Thank you all for so many

00:58:09.159 --> 00:58:10.360
great questions too.

00:58:10.360 --> 00:58:11.879
I'm sorry if there were any questions

00:58:11.879 --> 00:58:13.560
that we didn't get to,

00:58:13.560 --> 00:58:15.239
but there were so many good ones in the chat.

00:58:15.800 --> 00:58:17.560
Have a great rest of the day, everybody.

